- `app/components/ActionButtonsLayout/ActionButtonsLayout.tsx`
- `app/features/CustomerEvaluation/components/CustomerEvaluationTab/features/CommentList/CommentList.tsx`
- `app/pages/Result/features/TariffsOverview/components/TariffTile/features/Chips/ChipsDesktop.tsx`

## Folder layout patterns

Pick the shallowest structure that matches responsibility; nest `components/`, `features/`, `layouts/`, `assets/`, `utils/` as the tree grows.

### A — Root + co-located entry (common under `app/components/`)

```text
Foo/
  Foo.tsx
  Foo.module.scss
  Foo.test.tsx          # when tests exist
```

### B — Platform or variant split (Desktop / Mobile / App)

```text
Foo/
  FooDesktop/
    FooDesktop.tsx
    FooDesktop.module.scss
  FooMobile/
    FooMobile.tsx
```

### C — Feature slice with sub-features

```text
FeatureName/
  components/
    SubWidget/
      SubWidget.tsx
  features/
    DeepFeature/
      DeepFeature.tsx
  FeatureName.tsx
```

### D — Page-local component

```text
app/pages/Result/features/SomeFeature/components/SomeWidget/SomeWidget.tsx
```

**Imports:** prefer direct paths to source files (no `index.ts` barrels except where the repo explicitly allows multi-export or lazy-load). See **`rules-folder-organization.mdc`**.

## TypeScript + export pattern

- **`export default function`** for the main component in the file (matches most listed files).
- Return type: **`ReactElement`** (import `ReactElement` from `"react"`; avoid `React.ReactElement` per **`rules-bundle-react.mdc`**).
- Props: dedicated **`interface FooProps`** with **`readonly`** on every field.
- Extend DOM props only when wrapping a native element, e.g. `extends ButtonHTMLAttributes<HTMLButtonElement>`.

### Template — presentational component

```tsx
import type { ReactElement, ReactNode } from "react";

import styles from "./Foo.module.scss";

interface FooProps {
  readonly title: ReactNode;
  readonly className?: string;
}

export default function Foo(props: FooProps): ReactElement {
  return (
    <section className={styles.Foo}>
      <h2 className={styles.Foo_title}>{props.title}</h2>
    </section>
  );
}
```

### Template — wrapper with native element props

```tsx
import classNames from "classnames";
import type { ButtonHTMLAttributes, ReactElement, ReactNode } from "react";

import styles from "./Foo.module.scss";

interface FooProps extends ButtonHTMLAttributes<HTMLButtonElement> {
  readonly children: ReactNode;
  readonly active: boolean;
}

export default function Foo({ children, active, className, ...props }: FooProps): ReactElement {
  return (
    <button
      {...props}
      type="button"
      className={classNames(styles.Foo, active ? styles.Foo___active : styles.Foo___inactive, className)}
    >
      {children}
    </button>
  );
}
```

## Styling (SCSS modules + BEM)

- One **`.module.scss`** next to the component (or next to each variant file).
- **Block** name matches the component: `.Foo { ... }`.
- **Element**: `&_title` → `.Foo_title`.
- **Modifier**: `&___active` → `.Foo___active` (three underscores in source; see existing components).

Use **`classnames`** when combining module classes with optional `className` from props.

## Conditional rendering (project utilities)

Align with **`rules-typescript-clean-code.mdc`** and **`rules-bundle-react.mdc`**:

- **`renderIfNotNull(value, render)`** — nullable data → UI.
- **`renderWithCondition(condition, whenTrue, whenFalse?)`** — boolean gates.
- **Enum-keyed maps** for multiple variants (define **outside** the component):

```tsx
import type { ReactElement } from "react";

import type { SomeEnum } from "enums/SomeEnum.enum";

const SUBVIEW_MAP: Record<SomeEnum, () => ReactElement> = {
  [SomeEnum.A]: () => <AView />,
  [SomeEnum.B]: () => <BView />,
};

// In JSX: {SUBVIEW_MAP[someEnum]()}
```

Device-specific trees often use **`useDeviceOutputRenderer`** (see `app/hooks/useDeviceOutputRenderer.tsx`) or separate `*Desktop` / `*Mobile` components in the file list.

## Data / effects

- Prefer **hooks** in `hooks/` for non-trivial logic; keep the component thin.
- Use **`useEffect`** only for real side effects (e.g. logging route errors in **`ErrorInfo`**).
- Avoid `useMemo` / `useCallback` unless needed for expensive work or referential stability (**`rules-typescript-clean-code.mdc`**).

